content.content: The Oxford comma is an optional comma that is used before the words 'and' or 'or' at the end of a list: Example: Please bring me a pencil, an eraser, and a notebook. or Please bring me a pencil, an eraser and a notebook. Whether or not you use the Oxford comma is generally up to you. However, omitting it can sometimes cause some strange misunderstandings, as the following two examples will show: Example 1: I love my parents, Elton John and Lady Gaga. The meaning of this sentence is that you love your parents who are Elton John and Lady Gaga. Example 2: I love my parents, Elton John, and Lady Gaga. In this sentence, you list the three things you love the most: your parents, Elton John, and Lady Gaga. The Oxford comma is optional, but use it if you see that it can clarify the meaning of the sentence. The Oxford comma is also known as the serial comma.

content.content: What is the difference between an independent and a dependent clause? An independent clause is a clause that can stand on its own, by itself. It does not need to be joined to any other clauses, because it contains all the necessary information to be a complete sentence. You can divide the following sentence in two and still have two grammatically correct sentences – they are independent of each other. Example: The end of the concert was especially pleasing, and I liked the song they played. Sentence 1: The end of the concert was especially pleasing. (Independent clause) Sentence 2: I liked the song they played. (Independent clause) When we have two independent clauses together like this, we separate them using a comma. A dependent clause, on the other hand, does not express a complete thought and cannot form a simple sentence by itself. Example: He likes to eat but doesn’t really like to cook. Sentence 1: He likes to eat. (Independent clause) Sentence 2: Doesn’t really like to cook. (Dependent clause) In the example, the clause is dependent because it lacks a subject. When you have an independent clause and a dependent clause together you do not separate them using a comma.

content.content: An adverb is a word that modifies (describes) a verb, an adjective, another adverb, or a phrase. Example: - an adverb modifying a verb: A lion! Run quickly! - an adverb modifying an adjective: He's an overly sensitive young man. - an adverb modifying another adverb: The restaurant is almost fully booked. - an adverb modifying a phrase: Clearly, you haven't done your homework. A good way to understand adverbs is to think about them as the words that provide context. Specifically, adverbs provide a description of how, where, when, in what manner, and to what extent something is done or happens. The majority of adverbs end in -ly, but this is not a set rule. For example, words like 'fast', 'far', 'right', and 'never' are some of the most common adverbs in the English language.

content.content: Action verbs tell what the subject of a sentence is doing. Action verbs can be used to express physical or mental actions. There are thousands of action verbs. A few examples: run, plan, jump, speak, think, organise ... Linking verbs, on the other hand, are used to describe states of being, like the verb 'to be', or to describe senses, like the verb 'to feel'. They do not show any action; they simply link the subject with the rest of the sentence. For example, in the sentence 'They are fast', the word 'are' is the linking verb that connects 'they' and 'fast' to show the relationship between the two words. Become, seem, and any form of the verb 'to be' (is, are, was, has been...) are linking verbs. Also, all sense verbs (look, smell, touch, appear, sound, taste, feel) can be linking verbs.

content.content: Medieval romance is a genre of literature that appears in England in the time period 1066 to 1485. Medieval romances usually tell the story of a heroic knight who goes on a quest. The romances reworked elements from folklore, fairytales, and history. There are examples of Medieval romances written in prose as well as in verse. The stories are set in distant times and faraway places, and unusual events are depicted. Most Medieval romances contain a supernatural element. Examples of Medieval romance are Le Morte D'Arthur by Thomas Malory, Sir Gawain and the Green Knight, and Troilus and Criseyde.

content.content: A prepositional phrase contains a preposition (a word that specifies place, direction, or time) and an object of the preposition (a noun phrase or pronoun that follows the preposition). Also, prepositional phrases often contain a modifier. Modifiers describe something or make the meaning more specific. Example: Is he really going out with that girl? With modifier: Is he really going out with that lovely girl? She went into the woods. With modifier: She went into the cold, dark woods.
